    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Judging Bush on the Death Penalty</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Margaret P Levy letter on May 14 article on Gov George W Bush and his views regarding death penalty in Texas</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Bush Candidacy Puts Focus on Executions'' (front page, May 14):</p>
        <p>Important and lifesaving as the Illinois moratorium, the Innocence Project at Benjamin N. Cardozo Law School and brave individual efforts may be, the real issue is that Texas has killed 127 human beings, not that one or more may have been innocent.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Bush Candidacy Puts Focus on Executions'' (front page, May 14):</p>
        <p>Important and lifesaving as the Illinois moratorium, the Innocence Project at Benjamin N. Cardozo Law School and brave individual efforts may be, the real issue is that Texas has killed 127 human beings, not that one or more may have been innocent.</p>
        <p>We need to recognize that the death penalty is both cruel and incompatible with an enlightened humanity in the 21st century. And we need to be sure that the next president, with power to appoint Supreme Court justices, is not irrevocably committed to the execution of our citizens, no matter how heinous their actions.</p>
        <p>MARGARET P. LEVY  Hartford, May 15, 2000</p>
      </block>
